Business Understanding 1¶

Describe the purpose of the data set you selected (i.e., why was this data collected in the first place?). How will you measure the effectiveness of a good algorithm? Why does your chosen validation method make sense for this specific dataset and the stakeholders needs?

Our data is selected from user submitted ratings on AirBnB listings in the NYC area. AirBnB hosts are scored by their tenants across multiple categories. Categories can include the location, dollar value, check in easiness, cleanliness of the rental, or even the accuracy of the posting. This greatly benefits both the renter and AirBnB. From a renters perspective: they are able to trust the validity of postings and the hosts as they use the site. From AirBnBs business perspective, crowd sourcing their due diligence allows for employees to put issues as they appear, while leaving renters and hosts who are satisfied alone.

Clustering provides an interesting solution where AirBnB could, with a sufficient algorithm on bedrooms and bathrooms, split their listings into more explainable groups. To determine the validity of these algorithms, we will observe the accuracy of cluster classifications. This is a fairly straight-forward and interpretable measure that is easily used to judge the validity of various clustering methodologies.

Data Understanding 1¶

Describe the meaning and type of data (scale, values, etc.) for each attribute in the data file. Verify data quality: Are there missing values? Duplicate data? Outliers? Are those mistakes? How do you deal with these problems?

Data Meaning Type¶

Our data has 35 attributes across 75749 instances. Each instance refers to 1 rental property listing. Our group would inevitably exclude some of the attributes such as name, host name, calendar last scraped, and last review date. These fields proved to be non useful.

The way this data is collected and aggregated was an interesting process to our group: When a rental property owner registers their property on the application, they are filling in a lot of these attributes themselves. However, the rating attributes of the property itself is determined by the renter, or the end-user. Having these attributes be populated by many people to reach an aggregate gives a honest insight into the quality of both the rental and the host.

Looking at the above histograms, we can classify all columns as skewed. Therefore, we will now classify outliers as values outside the range (Q1 - 1.5 * IQR) , (Q3 + 1.5 * IQR).

In [16]:
lower_bounds = []
upper_bounds = []
maximums = []
columns = outlier_df.columns
outlier_count = []

for col in outlier_df.columns:
    Q3 = np.quantile(outlier_df[col], 0.75)
    Q1 = np.quantile(outlier_df[col], 0.25)
    Max = max(outlier_df[col])
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_range = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    
    if lower_range < 0:
        lower_range = 0
    
    upper_range = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    
    outliers = len(outlier_df[(outlier_df[col] > upper_range) | (outlier_df[col] < lower_range)])
    
    lower_bounds.append(lower_range)
    upper_bounds.append(upper_range)
    maximums.append(Max)
    outlier_count.append(outliers)
    
bounds_df = pd.DataFrame(list(zip(columns, lower_bounds, upper_bounds, maximums, outlier_count)), 
                         columns = ["Column","Lower","Upper", "Maximum", "Outlier Count"])

pd.options.display.float_format = '{:.5f}'.format

Column-Specific Outlier Handling¶

Now we have the lower and upper bounds of our outlier ranges. However, some columns might have outliers - but they're valid data points. Let's take them one by one.

Accommodates: A maximum of 16 is certainly understandale and could very realistically be true. Although some of these rentals that claim to accommodate 16 people are oddly small, that value of 16 still isn't outlandish. Therefore, we'll keep those in.

Bathrooms: Although the maximum of 15.5 is large, that Airbnb has 14 bedrooms. Therefore, it is likely this is just a very large rental.

Bedrooms: The rental with 14 bathrooms is the same one discussed immediately above. Therefore, this value checks out.

Price: Logically, a maximum of $999 makes sense. And since we don't quite have a way to validate or invalidate these prices, we will leave them in.

Minimum nights: The ~3000 rows with a minimum nights value over 8.5 is quite daunting. It is likely that some of the higher values (above 50) are mistakes, as Airbnbs with a minimum night stay of 50 nights is unheard of. Therefore, we will cap the maximum value for this column at 10.

Maximum nights: Similar to minimum nights, it is very likely that these higher values are mistakes. Since Airbnbs do allow very long stays, we will cap the maximum at 365.

Availability 365: The logical maximum for this column is 365. This is the maximum for this column, so these values are valid.

Number of reviews: The upper bound here of ~50 reviews is fairly low. In fact, the maximum of 489 reviews isn't outlandish either. Therefore, we can't classify any of these values as mistakes, so these values will remain.

Review Scores Accuracy - Review Scores Value: The maximum here (according to the data dictionary) is 10. Therefore, these columns are valid.

Reviews per month: While the maximum of 24.53 is impressive, it cannot be ruled out. Therefore, we will keep those values.

# try with Agglomerative Clustering
from sklearn.cluster import AgglomerativeClustering

X1 = data2[['Bathrooms','Bedrooms']]

params = []
for link in ['ward', 'complete', 'average']:
    for n_bb in range(5,6):

        # append on the clustering
        cls_bb = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=n_bb, linkage=link)
        cls_bb.fit(X1)
        newfeature_bb = cls_bb.labels_ # the labels from kmeans clustering
        
        y = data2['Grade']
        X = data2.drop(['Grade', 'Bathrooms', 'Bedrooms'], axis=1)
        X = np.column_stack((X,pd.get_dummies(newfeature_bb)))
        
        acc = cross_val_score(clf,X,y=y,cv=cv)
        params.append((n_bb,acc.mean()*100,acc.std()*100)) # save state
        
        
        print ("C=",n_bb,link,"Average accuracy = ", acc.mean()*100, "+-", acc.std()*100)
        
        temp_acc = round(acc.mean()*100,2)
        temp_lwr = temp_acc - round(acc.std()*100,2)
        temp_upr = temp_acc + round(acc.std()*100,2)
    
        temp_df = pd.DataFrame(data = {'Category':['Agglomerative'], 'Param 1':['Link:'+str(link)], 'Param 2':['Clusters:'+str(n_bb)], 'Acc':[temp_acc], 'Lwr':[temp_lwr], 'Upr':[temp_upr]})
        stats_df = pd.concat([stats_df, temp_df])
        print(temp_label)

# DBSCAN

from sklearn.cluster import DBSCAN

params = []
for eps in [0.1, 0.125, 0.15]:
    for mpts in range(5,6):

        # append on the clustering
        cls_bb = DBSCAN(eps=eps, min_samples=mpts)
        cls_bb.fit(X1)
        newfeature_bb = cls_bb.labels_ # the labels from kmeans clustering

        y = data2['Grade']
        X = data2.drop(['Grade', 'Bathrooms', 'Bedrooms'], axis=1)
        X = np.column_stack((X,pd.get_dummies(newfeature_bb)))
        
        acc = cross_val_score(clf,X,y=y,cv=cv)
        params.append((n_bb,acc.mean()*100,acc.std()*100)) # save state

        print (eps,mpts,"Average accuracy = ", acc.mean()*100, "+-", acc.std()*100)
        
        temp_acc = round(acc.mean()*100,2)
        temp_lwr = temp_acc - round(acc.std()*100,2)
        temp_upr = temp_acc + round(acc.std()*100,2)
    
        temp_df = pd.DataFrame(data = {'Category':['DBSCAN'], 'Param 1':['Eps:'+str(eps)], 'Param 2':['MinPts:'+str(mpts)], 'Acc':[temp_acc], 'Lwr':[temp_lwr], 'Upr':[temp_upr]})
        stats_df = pd.concat([stats_df, temp_df])

Between KMeans, Agglomerative, and DBSCAN methods, performance is relatively stable at just over 50% accuracy. Therefore, this should open up the debate if clustering is worth the effort for this problem, especially considering that the random forest performs just as well.

KMeans is more useful in the sense that it doesn't consume too much time or memory - but it doesn't perform at any better rate than the other options.

In terms of cost, Agglo. and DBSCAN are much more computational expensive, leading to long training times and large required amounts of memory. While a company such as AirBnb should not have an issue running these models, this can become a hurdle for other populations, such as students or data scientists at a company that hasn't invested much into this field.

Modeling and Evaluation 4¶

The accuracy not being as high was a large area of concern for our group. Unfortunately we did not receive an accuracy % as high as we would like.

K-Means¶

K-Means is typically used to compress complex and larger datasets into partionaed clusters that are simpler. K-Means is using the distance between points

Pros:

-Simple to use, junior data scientists could use these models well

-Easiest to interpret

-For larger datasets like ours, we can create a lot of clusters

Cons:

-If we were to run this model several times, we run the risk of getting different results. K-Means lacks consistency

-Predicting the number to use for the k value is difficult

Agglomerative¶

We used this by using linkage distance to merge the pairs of sample data.

Pros:

-The output is the easiest to interpret. Hirearchical clustering is very simple and sleek.

-The dendrogram that we receive from an output gives us a relatively good starting point of how many numbers of classes we can group into

Cons: -Cost. Compute costs primarily. -Extreme sensitivity to outliers -Time complexity

DB Scan¶

We use DBscan to calculate the number of data points within each cluster

Pros: -No need to specify the number of clusters beforehand -Outliers are not an issue

Cons: -Differing densities can throw the model off -Choosing an eps value is not simple -The algorithim starts within a random point so border points are not as easily defined

Deployment¶

Did we achieve our goals¶

Unfortunately not. The accuracy did not improve significantly. We wanted to give Airbnb a tool to categorize their listings in an almost definite way. Unfortunately we were not able to accurately cluster the listings in a way that would prove to be a net add to Airbnb's business.

If not, can we reign in the utility of our modeling¶

In a way, this is the intended utility. As a group we realized that clustering might not be the most pertinent issue that Airbnb could seek to gain advantage from. This still serves to be useful as knowing a direction to not head down is a lot better than not having any direction at all.

How useful is our modeling for interested parties, and how we would deploy¶

The models that we have used above give us a roadmap that would allow AirBnb to split their listings into easily categorized groupings. If depoloyed, this model would introduce a feature when it came to listing and locating properties where users on the listing side could tag the features they either want selected or can offer.

From a user perspective: Users benefit from the models we have put in place by getting a better experience when it comes to booking rentals. When selecting properties users would be able to select some pictures of features that they would want for their rental property. Examples that come to mind could be "spacious living room, lofted ceilings, garage style parking". The examples for this continue, but with this data and the models used, I think the users would greatly benefit from this.

What other data should be collected¶

One other big data point I think we should capture is how often listings are actually being used (the % of listings that are being used/the total amount of listings available). New York for example often has weekends where more people are staying in rental properties (Fashion Week, Tennis' US Open, NYC marathon, Super Bowl, etc..). Weekends like this are bound to capture more out of towners seeking temporary housing accomodations. Having an increase in demand will allow listers of properties to be able to charge more money for their listings.

How often would we need to update our model¶

Paying attention to real estate is always a very active endeavor. With the nature of real estate being what it is, I feel that our data would need to be updated daily. New listings tend to pop up on Airbnb daily and it is important to note what prices those new properties are being rented out at. Updating the data daily will also allow Airbnb to have a more accurate handle on the demand surges. Having a accurate pricing point during these demand increases will allow the lister to feel that they are not losing out on potential money.

Exceptional Work¶

You have free reign to provide additional analyses or combine analyses.

In order to see if any improvements can be made a few more clustering algorithms will be used. Mean shift clustering and BIRCH will be used. Mean shift clustering should make our clusters more robust to outliers and will not require us to input a number of clusters to run. BIRCH is an algorithm that performs well on large datasets. Something that our previous algorithms had issues with considering the size of our data.
